english:
  title: On Cotton
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The cotton of the South shines brighter than snow,
    Scattered white across the mat like winter's fall.
    The small spindle turns with creaking sound,
    As soft hands card it thin as autumn clouds.

    A woman from the eastern house sits through the night,
    Her spinning wheel winds thread upon the spool,
    Her fingers dance upon the loom,
    Clicking, clicking—the shuttle flies, her hands grow numb with cold.

    Half she'll fashion into garments for her child,
    Half she'll weave to send to those at the frontier's edge.
    Anxious thoughts consume her, sleep won't come,
    The lonely lamp flickers—its light, her only companion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem celebrates cotton work as both domestic labor and patriotic duty, with the woman dividing her output between family care and support for soldiers at the border.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the whiteness and softness of cotton and the woman's hardship creates the emotional tension of the piece.
